Vice President Yemi Osinbajo yesterday said the federal government was exploring possibilities and opportunities to ensure that broadband connection is available to Nigerians. Osinbajo spoke when he received a delegation from US-based technology giants, Microsoft Corporation, at the Presidential Villa, Abuja. He said the present administration also planned to use technology to reduce some of the deficits in healthcare and educational systems. The delegation led by Mr. Phil Spencer, the Executive Vice President of Gaming at Microsoft, also discussed the firm’s plan to set up African Development Centres in two locations on the continent; Nigeria and Kenya.  Nigeria spends huge forex on food imports in face of dwindling oil prices Osinbajo absent from office Terrorism: Nigeria seeks review of int’l regulations Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin